cord if no tasks are found, which helps keep the history uncluttered.\n\nNow I'm reconsidering the broader design—the `listTasksFn` runs repeatedly in the orchestration loop and creates a run record each time, but I'm wondering if those records are actually useful or just noise since the real work happens in the main phase with its own run record. That said, the requirement specifically mentions handling the empty result case, so I should focus on that scenario rather than redesigning the whole approach.\n\nLooking at the implementation details, I realize the Runner layer can't know whether `list-tasks` will return empty results until after the workflow completes and the output is parsed. So the deletion logic needs to happen after the run finishes. My approach is to modify `listTasksFn` in `server.go` to delete the run record when the task list comes back empty, add a helper to properly count only open tasks so the check is accurate, and then write tests to verify the behavior.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3221,"cache_read_input_tokens":28125,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3221},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"88adcd43-a2b6-4c68-8f0c-4f6b9fedf8a8","uuid":"6e6da01e-3d5c-4d7d-9c1c-c5725a9c7a40"}
